"&#xa0;\nWritten Evidence by Professor P.C. Lee&#xa0;\nExecutive summary:As a \npast president of the Primate Society of Great Britain, a scientific body established for the\n promotion of research into primate biology, conservation, and captive care, I would like to \nprovide\n some comments \nfor\n this enquiry.\n My expertise is not with regard to the numbers of primates held privately, but rather with the fundamental issues of the adequacy of the protection of primate welfare \nfor pet primates \nand the appropriateness of the keeping \nof primates as “pets”. \n&#xa0;\nAs a result of my \n39 years of \nexperience with non-human primate biology, behaviour and conservation\n both in the wild and captivity\n, I can perceive no ethical, husbandry, conservation or historical justifications for continuing to \nallow the keeping of primates as companion animals in the UK.\n&#xa0;\na)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nShould primates be kept in private ownership as “pets”?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nb)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAre primates adequately protected by current legislation?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nc)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n Implementation of a ban&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n9 Jan., 2014\nFootnotes and references\n&#xa0;\n 1 book, 4 edited volumes, over 65 peer reviewed scientific papers.\n For example: Monkey Sanctuary, Looe; Alan Knight, International Animal Rescue; Monkey World, Dorset\n European Commission guidelines for the keeping of primates: \nhttp:\n//ec.europa.eu/environment/chemicals/lab_animals/pdf/fische_suite.pdf\n \nJudge, D. S., &amp; Carey, J. R. (2000). Postreproductive life pre\ndicted by primate patterns. \nJournal of Gerontology Series A: Biological Sciences and Medical Sciences, 55(4), B201-B209\n.\n \nSpinelli, S., Chefer, S., Suomi, S. J., Higley, J. D., Barr, C. S., &amp; Stein, E. (2009). Early-life stress induces long-term morphologic changes\n in primate brain. Archives of General P\nsychiatry, 